#custompergola #pergola #pergolas #pergoladesign #buildingprojects #backyarddesign

Do you need to bore a hole in concrete? 
#concretecutting #remodelaholic #pergola #pérgola #pergoladesign #diyprojects 

Hey this is Justin at Remodelaholic, this video shows you how to drill a 10 inch hole in concrete using a concrete bore drill!  If you have the budget, it’s worth it.

This video is perfect for anyone planning to install pergolas, gazebos, or any other type of structure on a concrete footing!

I hired a concrete cutter to drill (7)10 inch holes in existing concrete for my custom pergola footings.  It was worth it to have this hired out to keep a nice clean look on the existing concrete.  It didn’t take too long once things where set up.  About a half day of work for these holes.

In the first part of the video I was prepping the area with a anchor for the drill press.  With the drill press anchored down tight to the concrete, it allowed it to cut a nice clean hole.

Stay tuned for the next progress video of prepping the footings for inspection.

Today I am pouring concrete footings for the backyard custom pergola.  I was able to get the holes to pass inspection now it’s time to fill them in.  I have #4 rebar suspended and ready centered in the footing 3” off the ground. 
#footings #pouringconcrete #remodelaholic 

It took about 2.5 bags of 80lb concrete bags to fill the holes.  Each hole took about one half hour to fill each one. 

The landscaper was able to get a funny pipe in place in the hole next to the grass, so I could tie into the drip irrigation that was going to water hanging backets and pots around the pergola.  That was great timing to get that in.  Now they don’t have to have a hose over the patio to water the plants.

Once it was filled I leveled it with a small hand trowel level to the existing patio.  Now we just need to wait a few days to add the post brackets.

Browse our selection of crafts below to find new simple and fun ways to use 4x4s. From an outdoor dice game and decorative pencil holder to holiday crafts like Fourth of July glitter firecrackers and a candy cane stocking holder, there are projects for all seasons.

#DIY #Craft #DoItYourself #woodwork dWork #WoodProjects #Remodeling #Remodel #KeepingBusy

I made these little paper blossoms a few months ago and have been toying around with them ever since, trying to decide which wreath, box or other item to attach them to.  I finally decided that they were cute enough to make a simple little display of their own.  What do you think?

#roses #paper #paperflower #icanbuymyselfflowers #paperrose

Here I am installing post brackets for the backyard pergola on the new footings.  I chose to use the Simpson Strong Tie CPT88Z ZMAX Galvanized 8x8 Concealed Post Base. 
#diypergola #diyprojects #construction #shorts

Links below contain affiliate links that help support our channel.  Thanks in advance!

Here is the link for the post base:  https://amzn.to/3NaxDhj 
I wanted to use these brackets and try them out to see if I would want to do more pergolas with them.

I let the concrete cure for a few days before drilling 1/2” holes in them with a impact driver, for the two 6” blots that I used to anchor them down.  Here is the link for the bolts: https://amzn.to/3ITPYN8

After cleaning out the holes with an air compressor and a wire brush,  I filled in the hole halfway with a two part epoxy.  Here is the link for the epoxy: https://amzn.to/3qhO5TY
Here is a link for the epoxy dispensing tool: https://amzn.to/43FWSgV

The epoxy is there to lock in the bolt.  Just make sure that you get all the holes ready first before you start using the epoxy.  Also if you don’t have a strong enough drill to drill in the bolts you will waist a good tube of epoxy because of wasting time trying to borrow a impact driver that is strong enough to drill in the anchor.  Just saying!  Don’t waist your money. 

Once those where in it was time to start the fun part of building the pergola.

Be sure the check out the previous videos of this custom pergola.

Now that the lumber is delivered, I am able to get the cedar pergola lumber prepped and stained. 

#shorts #stainingwood #pergola 

I started prepping the cedar posts and rolled on the stain.  I used a deck brush to brush off the wood from any dust, then I was able to stain.  I wanted to pre stain the posts on saw horses because I thought that would be the easiest way to control the stain.  I added two coats of stain per the product recommendations and warranty. 

Because it was rough cedar wood I used a roller with a 3/4” nap to really get in the wood grain.  Once the sun came out it dried really quick and I was able to add a second coat within 60 minutes of the first.

Let me know in the comments if you want to know the stain product I used.  I will make another short video just on the stain.

Once all the stain was on and dried, I started prepping the bases of the posts.  I had to use a chain saw to cut in a grove at the bottom about 5” high.  I found that the chain saw was a great tool for this project. 

Stay tuned and I will show you in the next video how it attaches to the base when it is upright.

Be sure to check out the previous videos of this custom pergola.

Don’t do what I did! the Rigid brand has been great tools for me over the years. If you buy a tool from Home Depot especially the Rigid brand you have access to a lifetime warranty for that tool. Which is awesome! I bought this Rigid mitersaw years ago and I have other tools that I purchased years ago and I haven’t registered them right away which is a problem. If you’re assuming that you’re going to be able to replace the saw when it’s broken or the tool well you can’t. You have to register the tool before 90 days after you purchased it. If you want me to show you that process in a video let me know. Thanks for watching now go build something great!
